.TH DMESG 8
.SH NAME
dmesg \- display kernel diagnostic messages
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B dmesg
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B dmesg
reads the kernel message ring buffer via
.B /dev/kmem
and prints all messages to standard output.
The ring buffer resides in far memory (carved from top of
conventional RAM) and contains messages from device drivers,
the memory manager, the process scheduler, and other
kernel subsystems.
.PP
Typical uses include diagnosing boot-time hardware problems,
verifying device driver attachment, and checking for kernel errors
after a system event.
.PP
The ring buffer is enabled and sized by the
.B dmesg=
parameter in
.BR /bootopts .
For example,
.B dmesg=4
allocates a 4K buffer (4096 bytes).
If
.B dmesg=
is not specified, the ring buffer is not created and
.B dmesg
will report that the buffer is not configured.
.PP
When the buffer is full, the oldest messages are silently discarded.
On a busy system,
.B dmesg
may not show messages from early boot.
.SH EXIT STATUS
.TP
.B 0
Messages were read successfully, or the ring buffer is not configured.
.TP
.B 1
/dev/kmem could not be opened or the ioctl failed.
.SH FILES
.TP
.B /dev/kmem
Memory device used to read the ring buffer.
.TP
.B /bootopts
Boot options file; the
.B dmesg=
parameter controls the buffer size in K.
.SH "SEE ALSO"
.BR syslog (8).
